<h2>HVAC Systems in Maine</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Maine's climate demands robust heating systems capable of handling temperatures that regularly drop below 0¬∞F, while still providing efficient cooling during summer months when temperatures can reach the 80s and 90s. The heating season typically extends from October through April, representing approximately 7,000-8,500 heating degree days annually, significantly higher than the national average. This extended heating season means that heating efficiency takes priority over cooling efficiency when selecting HVAC systems.</p>

<p>For cooling applications, SEER ratings of 16-18 are recommended in Maine, balancing efficiency with cost-effectiveness given the relatively short cooling season. However, heating efficiency becomes paramount, making heat pumps with high HSPF (Heating Seasonal Performance Factor) ratings of 10+ highly desirable. Cold-climate heat pumps, specifically designed for regions like Maine, can effectively heat homes even when outdoor temperatures drop to -15¬∞F or lower.</p>

<p>Humidity control is another important consideration, particularly during Maine's humid summers and the dry heating season. Modern HVAC systems with variable-speed components can better manage humidity levels year-round, improving comfort and indoor air quality while reducing energy consumption through more precise temperature and humidity control.</p>

