<h2>Maine Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Maine offers robust incentive programs that significantly improve the economics of solar and HVAC installations. The cornerstone incentive is the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, then decreasing to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, and can be carried forward to future tax years if the credit exceeds current tax liability.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available for solar panel systems, battery storage, and solar water heating systems. The credit can be claimed against federal income taxes and covers all qualifying expenses including equipment, installation, permits, and interconnection fees. Homeowners can carry unused credits forward for up to five years, and there is no cap on the credit amount.</li>
<li><strong>State Solar Rebates:</strong> Maine offers solar rebates up to \$4,000 through various programs, including rebates for residential solar installations and community solar projects. The Governor's Energy Office administers several programs that provide direct rebates and low-interest financing options for qualifying installations.</li>
<li><strong>Central Maine Power Programs:</strong> CMP offers several energy efficiency programs including rebates for heat pumps (\$500-1,200), high-efficiency water heaters (\$300-600), and weatherization improvements. The utility also provides interconnection support for solar installations and maintains net metering programs that credit excess solar production at retail rates.</li>
<li><strong>Heat Pump Rebates:</strong> Efficiency Maine offers rebates up to \$2,100 for qualifying heat pump installations, with additional rebates available for low-income households. These rebates apply to both ducted and ductless heat pump systems that meet minimum efficiency requirements.</li>
<li><strong>Property Tax Exemptions:</strong> Maine provides a 100% property tax exemption for solar installations, meaning the added home value from solar panels is not subject to property taxes. This exemption applies to both the equipment and installation costs, providing ongoing savings throughout the system's lifetime.</li>
</ul>

